THE LONG ROAD HOME
A Chronicle of the Skyrim Wardens

PART I: THE FOLDING
Kyboh reached for the Matrix.
Varon was holding it — the Aetherial Matrix, cool and dark in the Shadowscale's hands, pulsing faintly with a rhythm like a sleeping heartbeat. The crystal that had powered a Centurion for four thousand years. The component Hjolmar needed to build the gauntlet that would save Kyboh's life.
Kyboh reached for it the way he reached for everything — without thinking, without hesitating, without the fraction of a second's pause that a smarter man would have used to remember that Hjolmar had given him an Anchor of Stasis and told him to keep it on until the gauntlet was finished and not to touch anything tonal without it. The Anchor was in his pack. His enchanted bones were exposed. And the Matrix was right there, and it was warm, and it was his.
His fingers closed around the crystal.
The harmonic lock engaged instantly. The bone enchantment — the Titan's Tithe, migrated into his marrow, singing at a frequency only Dwemer architecture could hear — found its counterpart in the Matrix's tonal structure and synchronized. The resonance built in a fraction of a heartbeat, rising through frequencies that passed through audible and into something that made the brass walls of the workshop vibrate.
Kyboh tried to let go. His hand wouldn't open. The Matrix was fused to his palm — not physically, but tonally, the two frequencies locked together in a harmonic embrace that his flesh couldn't break.
Then the light came.
It started at his hands. Amber light, the exact colour of the Dwemer lamps, crawling up his arms like liquid, spreading across his chest, his neck, his face. His body was becoming translucent — not disappearing, not disintegrating, but converting. Flesh into sound. Bone into frequency. Mass into mathematics.
Things fell from him as the conversion spread. The Augur's focusing crystal hit the floor and bounced, ringing like a bell. Potions clattered and rolled. His dragonbone greatsword — the massive blade he'd carried since before the Pale Lady's tomb — struck the stone and split along stress fractures that the bone enchantment had been holding together. Four pieces. The sword that had been an extension of his body broke when his body stopped being there to hold it.
"KYBOH!" Saijah screamed.
He looked at her. His eyes were still his — amber, confused, not afraid, because Kyboh was never afraid of the things he should be afraid of. He looked confused the way he always looked confused, like the world had just done something he hadn't expected and he was trying to figure out what he'd done wrong.
Then the light contracted. The amber collapsed inward, pulling Kyboh's form into a single point of blinding intensity that hung in the air where he'd been standing for one impossibly long heartbeat.
Then it was gone. The point of light shot upward — through the ceiling, through the Cognitorium, through the Deep Lift shaft, through a mile of stone and ice — and vanished.
The workshop was empty where he'd been. Four pieces of a broken sword on the floor. Potions rolling to a stop against debris. The focusing crystal spinning slowly, its faint blue light fading.
Three seconds of silence.
Then the amber lamps turned crimson. Every light in the Cognitorium snapped from warm gold to harsh, pulsing red. A grinding, high-frequency vibration built in the walls — every bronze pipe in the archive screaming the same note. Heavy locks disengaged above them. Dozens. Simultaneously.
GEAR spun, eye clicking between red and amber.
"Safe Integration Protocol terminated. System-wide biological purge activated. All non-authorized organic material will be eradicated."
His eye clicked again.
"That would be you. Current survival probability: 4.2%. I recommend we leave immediately."

PART II: THE PURGE
The Cognitorium
They ran.
Bronze panels in the staircase walls slid open. Dwemer Spheres rolled out, unfolding into combat forms mid-stride — blade-arms deploying, crossbow bolts already loaded, their movements precise and identical in the way that only machines fighting on shared programming could be. Two from the archive level. Two more from alcoves on the staircase above.
The party fought up the spiral staircase in a desperate retreat. Every time they destroyed a sphere, a ceiling chute opened and a replacement dropped two rounds later. The room couldn't be cleared. It could only be survived.
Davinia's ice magic carved barriers across the staircase behind them, buying seconds as sphere after sphere crashed through the frozen walls. Orion's horn weakened the constructs' structure, making blades brittle, making gears stick. Alfonso fired bolt after bolt of lightning, each one ignoring the constructs' plating the way Hjolmar's forge had taught them — shock passes through brass like it isn't there.
Then a crossbow bolt caught Nora in the shoulder.
The impact spun her. She hit the staircase railing and went over. Davinia saw it happen — the girl's eyes going wide, the black soul gems swinging on their cords, her hands reaching for a hold that wasn't there.
Davinia lunged. The Wizard Hand — Ismara's ice architecture, faster than flesh, stronger than bone — closed around Nora's wrist and held. The construct of crystalline cold took the girl's full weight without cracking. Davinia hauled her back onto the staircase with a strength that was Ismara's, not hers, and she didn't have time to think about what that meant.
"Don't stop!" Davinia shouted, pulling Nora against her chest. "Move!"
She half-carried Nora up the last flight of stairs, ice forming under her boots to give her traction, the Crown humming with the effort of keeping its host alive while the archive tried to kill them.
They reached the docking port. The Deep Lift platform was still locked in its clamp. Behind them, spheres were pouring up the staircase. Through the Cognitorium's viewports, they could see Blackreach below — every Dwemer structure lighting up from amber to crimson, the underground continent waking from four thousand years of sleep.
What they were fighting here was a fraction of what was activating below.
They boarded the platform. A sphere lunged for the edge as the lift began to rise. Saijah put an arrow through its lens. It fell, sparking, into the dark.
The platform entered the shaft. Crossbow bolts sparked off the walls as they rose out of range.
The Ascent
The Deep Lift shaft. Five hundred feet of enclosed vertical tunnel. The platform grinding upward at a speed it could not be hurried past.
Maintenance hatches banged open. Spiders dropped onto the platform — smaller than the spheres, faster, their static shock attacks crackling between brass legs. Two hit the surface and immediately charged.
Kyboh would have been immune to the static. The Anchor of Stasis would have nullified the magical component. Kyboh would have stood in the middle of the platform and let them hit him while the others worked.
Kyboh wasn't here.
They fought the spiders with what they had. Saijah's arrows. Alfonso's diminishing reserves of lightning. Davinia's ice sealing hatches before more could emerge. Nora, one arm hanging useless from the crossbow bolt, casting silent Illusion spells that sent spiders attacking each other instead of the party.
Then the vents came. Horizontal openings in the shaft wall — two feet wide, spiders inside firing static shock through the gaps without fully emerging. Random targets. Unavoidable angles. Each hit draining magical energy from bodies that had already spent most of what they had in the workshop below.
Orion found his moment in the storm.
He raised his horn toward the shaft wall and played a sustained frequency — not the Diagnostic Song, not the Movement of Entropy, but something new. Something he built in the moment from the acoustic data he'd collected in the resonance chambers of the Dead City. A frequency tuned to the specific harmonic signature of Dwemer spider neural pathways.
The sound focused in the parabolic shaft like a weapon. Every spider in range seized — legs locking, static discharge cutting out, their tonal systems caught in a feedback loop created by their own architecture. The shaft went quiet for three full seconds.
Three seconds of silence in a vertical tunnel full of machines trying to kill them. Three seconds where nobody was being shocked, nobody was bleeding, nobody was losing the energy they needed to survive the next wave.
It wasn't dramatic. It wasn't a killing blow. It was a musician using the instrument a dead civilization had built for him, in the exact moment it mattered most, and buying his friends time to breathe.
Then the spiders recovered and the chaos resumed, but those three seconds had been enough to regroup, to seal three more hatches, to patch Nora's shoulder with a potion they couldn't afford to spare.
The platform climbed through the shaft. The spiders came in waves — dropping from hatches, climbing through the floor grating, punching manipulator legs through the metal beneath their feet. The platform shrank as safe footing disappeared. They fought standing on a disc that was dissolving under them.
Then the spiders stopped.
No enemies. The lift ground upward through empty shaft. Dim bronze light. The sound of the mechanism. Their own breathing.
From above — from the city level — a sound. Faint. Growing louder. Thousands of small metal legs on bronze flooring.
GEAR, quiet for the first time since the alarm:
"The city-level maintenance population consists of approximately eleven thousand Spider Worker units. They have been operating on autonomous maintenance routines for four millennia. They are now operating on biological purge routines."
He paused.
"The corridor between the Deep Lift and the Surface Lift is approximately four hundred meters."
Another pause.
"I would recommend running."
The Swarm
The lift locked into the city docking bay. The corridor ahead — the same wide, amber-lit hallway they'd explored hours ago — was unrecognisable.
The floor was a carpet of bronze. Thousands of Spider Workers, each the size of a dog, scuttling over and around each other in a flowing, electric mass. The made beds, the set plates, the wrench on the bench — buried under a tide of clicking, sparking metal. The brass horse figurine Kyboh had pocketed from a dead engineer's bedside was somewhere under that flood.
They were moving toward the party. Not fast. Not slow. The speed of a rising flood.
The Surface Lift was four hundred meters ahead. Through that.
Alfonso stopped at the corridor entrance. He turned to face the swarm. His hands were shaking — not from fear, but from exhaustion. He had been casting since the workshop. His reserves were gone. His FP was a memory. What he had left was measured in heartbeats, not spells.
He looked at the corridor full of eleven thousand machines and made a decision that had nothing to do with tactics and everything to do with the kind of man he was.
He planted his feet. He raised both hands. And he reached past his magic, past his reserves, past every limit that separated a spell from the person casting it. He reached into the place where his life force lived — the two songs, Namira's hunger and Peryite's order, warring in his chest — and he pulled them both.
The songs harmonized.
For one second — one impossible, excruciating second — the two divine frequencies that had been tearing him apart found a common note. Not peace. Not resolution. A shared purpose: destruction.
The spell erupted from his hands like a physical force. A beam of pure lightning — not the blue-white of Destruction magic, but something darker, something that crackled with amber and black, shot through with the sickly green of plague energy and the hollow darkness of Namira's hunger. It was wider than the corridor. It filled the space from wall to wall, floor to ceiling, and it traveled four hundred meters in less than a second.
Three full rooms of constructs ceased to exist.
The lightning didn't just destroy the spiders — it unmade them. Brass melted. Gears dissolved. The amber lamps in the corridor walls shattered from the shockwave. The carpet of machines became a carpet of molten metal and sparking fragments, steaming in the wake of something that should not have been possible from a single caster with no reserves left.
Alfonso dropped to his knees. Then to his hands. His breath was a thin, wet rasp. Blood ran from his nose, his ears, the corners of his eyes. His body was shutting down — not dying, not yet, but announcing with absolute clarity that it had been pushed past every structural limit that held it together.
One hit point. That was what was left of Alfonso Duet. One hit point between him and the void.
The others ran past him. Davinia grabbed his arm and hauled him upright. He couldn't walk on his own. She dragged him through the corridor of destruction he'd made, her ice-crystal hand locked around his forearm, and behind them the surviving swarm — the thousands that had been outside the blast radius — began to fill the cleared space, flowing over the bodies of their destroyed siblings with the mindless persistence of water finding a new path.
They were halfway to the Surface Lift when Ylva went down.
The Wolf
A spider hit her from behind — static shock to the base of the skull. She staggered. Two more hit her legs. She fell to one knee, axe swinging, clearing a circle around herself with pure violence.
Then a fourth spider climbed her back and drove its manipulator leg through the gap in her armour at the shoulder joint. The stab was precise, mechanical, designed for maintenance access on constructs three times Ylva's size. On flesh, it was catastrophic.
Ylva's eyes went wide. She looked down at the brass leg protruding from her chest. Blood — hot, real, hers — ran down the front of her armour.
She fell.
The party was ten meters ahead. They heard the impact of her body on the bronze floor. Saijah turned. Alfonso, hanging from Davinia's grip, turned his head.
Ylva was on the ground, surrounded by spiders, and she was not breathing.
Then she started screaming.
Not pain. Something deeper — a sound that came from a place inside her body that hadn't existed until this moment. Her back arched. Her armour buckled outward, seams splitting, buckles snapping. The spider still embedded in her shoulder was hurled free as her body expanded — muscles doubling, bones lengthening, her skin darkening to grey-black fur that erupted through her clothing like weeds through pavement.
Her hands — broad, calloused, made for gripping axes — twisted into claws. Her jaw elongated. Her teeth became fangs. The scream became a howl that filled the corridor from end to end, drowning out the clicking of eleven thousand spiders, drowning out the alarm, drowning out everything.
Ylva had died. And Hircine had refused to let her stay dead.
The werewolf that had been Ylva the Cleaver rose from the floor on legs that were not quite legs anymore. Nine feet of fur and muscle and rage, covered in blood that was already clotting, already healing, the wound that had killed her human body knitting shut in the time it took to draw a breath.
She looked at the swarm surrounding her. Her lips pulled back from fangs the length of daggers.
She tore into them.
The spiders were not designed for this. Their static shock was calibrated for organic neural pathways — Ylva's nervous system was no longer entirely organic. Their manipulator legs were designed for maintenance, not combat with something that could bite through brass. She ripped through the swarm like a scythe through wheat, clearing the corridor behind the retreating party with a fury that was not tactical, not measured, not human.
The party ran. The werewolf covered their retreat. Four hundred meters of corridor, three rooms cleared by Alfonso's blast and refilling with machines, and behind them all the sound of something massive and bestial destroying everything in its path.
The Final Lift
They reached the Surface Lift platform. The four brass resonator tubes stood at the cardinal points. The swarm was visible at the far end of the corridor — a living wall of bronze, flowing toward them, filling the space that Ylva's rampage had temporarily cleared.
The split happened without discussion. Half the party formed a line at the corridor entrance — the fifteen-foot chokepoint where the transit hub narrowed to a single passage. The other half ran for the tubes.
West. The first note rang out. Gears engaged below.
North. The second note. The platform jolted.
Saijah was at the chokepoint. The swarm hit the bottleneck and compressed — thousands of spiders trying to force through a fifteen-foot gap, climbing over each other, sparking against the walls. She didn't have Alfonso's reserves. She didn't have Ylva's beast form. She had a bow, a quiver of depleted arrows, and thirty feet of air.
South. The third note. The platform locked into the lift mechanism.
The swarm surged. GEAR deployed his Tonal Pulse — a concentrated burst that staggered every spider in the corridor mouth for one full second. In that second, Saijah moved.
She air-dashed. Thirty feet of vertical lift, clearing the chokepoint entirely, landing on the transit hub's upper maintenance gantry — a narrow walkway twenty feet above the swarm. From there, she could see the entire corridor: the flood of bronze below, the tube sequence nearly complete, her friends exposed on the platform.
She fired down into the swarm. Not to kill — there were too many, killing was meaningless — but to create. Each arrow hit the flood of metal and sent spiders scattering from the impact point, opening momentary gaps in the tide. She placed each shot to buy seconds at the chokepoint, redirecting the swarm's flow away from the defenders, turning the flood into eddies and whorls that fought each other instead of pushing forward.
East. The fourth note. The chord resolved.
"GO!" someone shouted.
Saijah dropped from the gantry. The platform was already moving — not the smooth, controlled descent they'd ridden down. An emergency ascent. The lift launched upward with a violence that threw everyone off their feet. The transit hub dropped away. Bronze walls blurred past. The tonal alarm faded from scream to hum to nothing.
The platform slammed into its surface housing. Gears locked. Bronze doors spiraled open.
Cold air. Snow. Wind.
Ylva stumbled through the doors last — human again, naked, covered in blood and oil and brass fragments. The transformation had reversed somewhere in the final sprint, her body shrinking from nine feet of beast to the broad-shouldered Nord woman they knew, leaving her without clothing, without armour, without any of the gear that had been shredded when Hircine's gift had remade her from the inside out.
She was alive. She was supposed to be dead.
She collapsed in the snow and didn't move.
The bronze doors ground shut. Locks engaged. Deep, final clanks that echoed through the frozen ground and faded to nothing.

PART III: THE ABSENCE
The Snow
Davinia fell to her knees at the edge of the lift housing. The cold hit her — real cold, surface cold, the kind that came from wind and open sky instead of ancient ice and tonal architecture. She knelt in the snow and punched the bronze doors. Once. Hard. The Wizard Hand left a dent in the metal that would be there for centuries.
She didn't say anything. The Crown was silent. Ismara had nothing to offer.
Alfonso walked away. He didn't stagger — he had moved past staggering into the territory of pure will, his body operating on the single hit point that separated him from death. He walked twenty feet from the group, stopped, and stood with his back to them, looking at the frozen tundra, breathing carefully. Blood was drying on his upper lip.
Saijah was crying. Not sobbing — the silent kind, tears freezing on her cheeks in the Pale wind, her bow still in her hand, her quiver empty. She stood at the edge of the depression and stared at the resonator tubes humming in the wind and let the tears come because there was nothing else to do with them.
Orion stood very still. His ring was cold on his finger. His horn hung at his side. He looked at the space between his companions — the gaps where they stood, the distances between them — and tried to understand how a group that had just fought through eleven thousand machines could feel so completely broken.
GEAR rolled out of the shaft behind them. His amber eye blinked in natural light for the first time in four thousand, two hundred and eighty-seven years.
He was very still. Very quiet.
"Surface conditions detected. Atmospheric composition: standard. Temperature: below optimal. Precipitation: frozen water crystals."
The eye rotated upward. Saw sky. Real sky. The pale grey of the northern Pale, stretching in every direction without a ceiling.
"I have not been above the surface level since my manufacture."
A long pause.
"Where are we going next?"
The Question
From the road below the depression, a voice.
"What happened? Where's the cat?"
Bjorn was standing beside the cart. Mable was hitched and waiting, her breath misting in the cold air. He had been here for hours — pacing, checking harnesses, listening to the faint sounds of alarm and combat echoing up through the ground beneath his feet. He had heard the lift mechanism fire. He had been counting heads since the doors opened.
He looked at their faces. He counted again.
"Where is he?"
They told him. The words came in fragments — from Davinia, from Saijah, from everyone at once and none of them making sense. Kyboh touched the Matrix. There was light. His body changed — became translucent, became sound, became nothing. Then he was gone. The Matrix was gone. Both folded into a point of light that shot upward through a mile of stone and vanished.
Gone where? They didn't know. Why? They didn't know that either.
Bjorn listened. He set down the harness he'd been adjusting. He looked at the ground for a long time.
"He's gone," Bjorn said. Not a question.
He didn't ask follow-up questions. He didn't offer comfort. He walked to the cart, checked the axle — the same way he always checked the axle, the same practiced motions, the same steady hands — and said:
"Get in. We need to keep moving."
They loaded into the cart. GEAR perched on the rail, his amber eye swiveling to take in the Pale. Ylva was wrapped in someone's bedroll, still naked, still silent, still processing the fact that she had died and come back as something with claws. Alfonso sat with his back against the cart wall and closed his eyes. Nora cradled her wounded shoulder.
Bjorn took up the reins. Mable leaned into the harness. The cart began to move south, through the frozen tundra, carrying heroes who had gone into the deep for a cure and come out with a wound.
Kyboh's seat on the cart was empty. His broken sword was in Davinia's pack, split into four pieces. His focusing crystal was in her pocket. His potions were distributed among the others.
Everything he'd left behind fit in a bag. The space he'd left behind didn't fit anywhere.

PART IV: THE FIRE
The First Night
They made camp in the foothills where the Pale began its long surrender to the Rift. The frozen tundra was softening — patches of brown earth showing through the snow, the first stubborn grasses pushing up between rocks. The air was still cold, but the killing edge was gone.
Bjorn built the fire larger than usual. He took his time with it. Deliberate. When it was burning well, he walked to the cart and came back with a bottle — Black-Briar Reserve. He'd been carrying it since the Thornheart Grove job. He'd been saving it.
He didn't explain. He sat down by the fire, uncorked the bottle, and poured cups. One for each of them. Then he poured a sixth cup and set it on the ground next to the empty space where Kyboh would be sitting.
The firelight caught the dark liquid. Nobody spoke.
"I've been driving you lot since Solitude," Bjorn said. His voice was steady. Measured. The voice of a man who had decided what he was going to say and was going to say it regardless of whether it hurt. "Through Falkreath, Riften, Winterhold, and whatever that brass hell was today. I've seen you fight vampires, dragons, and each other. I've seen you do things that would have sent a smarter man running."
He looked at the fire. Not at them.
"I never said much about it because it wasn't my place. I'm the driver. I get you where you're going and I keep the horse alive. That's the job."
He stopped. Drank. The bottle made a soft sound when he set it down.
"But that boy."
He was quiet for a moment. The fire cracked.
"He was loud. He was reckless. He broke things. He laughed at the wrong times. And he was the first one to throw himself between a stranger and something that wanted to kill them. Every single time. Without thinking. Without asking what was in it for him."
"I don't know if he's alive. That old man in the glacier — I don't trust him. I never trusted him. Something about the way he looked at the kid... like he was measuring a coat he wanted to try on."
He picked up the sixth cup. Held it.
"But I know this. Whatever happened to him, wherever he is, he didn't quit on you. He didn't walk away. He was taken. And that means we owe him. Not a funeral. A rescue."
He poured the sixth cup onto the ground. The liquid darkened the earth and steamed in the cold air.
"So drink up. And when you're done being sad, start being angry. Because we're getting him back."
They drank. The Black-Briar Reserve burned going down — the good kind of burn, the kind that reminded you that you were alive and that being alive was worth something even when it didn't feel like it.
The fire settled. The silence stretched. Each of them sat with the weight of the day and the absence at their fire and whatever private grief they carried for a loud, reckless Khajiit who had reached for a crystal without thinking and disappeared.
Then GEAR spoke.
His voice was different. Not the chipper brightness of the archive tour. Not the clinical precision of the tactical assessment. Something between them — a tone that suggested the brass sphere was running calculations on data it had never been designed to process.
"You are allocating a portion of a finite consumable resource to a person who is not present and cannot consume it."
He paused. His eye clicked.
"This is not efficient."
Another pause. Longer. The lens dimmed slightly, then brightened.
"But you are not doing it for efficiency. You are doing it because the act of waste itself carries meaning. The sacrifice of something useful in honour of something valued."
He was still for a long time. The fire reflected in his amber lens.
"I have maintained the Cognitorium for four thousand, two hundred and eighty-seven years. I allocated resources to systems that would never be used again, for researchers who would never return. I did not understand why I continued. My programming did not require it."
The lens clicked once. Twice.
"I believe I was pouring the sixth cup."
The fire cracked. Nobody corrected him. Nobody explained. Some truths don't need context. A machine that had been grieving for four millennia without having the framework to call it grief had just found the word, and the word was a cup of Black-Briar Reserve poured onto frozen ground for someone who wasn't coming back.
The Aftermath
Ylva grabbed Alfonso's arm and pulled him to his feet. He didn't resist — one hit point left no room for resistance. She dragged him behind a stand of scrub pines at the edge of camp with a grip that was half desire and half something more desperate, the specific need of a woman who had died an hour ago and wanted to feel alive in the most immediate way available.
What happened behind the pines was brief and loud enough that the rest of the camp heard it and chose not to comment. When Ylva emerged, she was in werewolf form again — not the desperate, death-triggered transformation of the corridor, but something more controlled. She stood at the tree line for a moment, nine feet of grey-black fur and muscle, breathing the night air through a muzzle that was testing scents it had never catalogued.
Then the transformation reversed. The fur receded. The claws retracted. The bones shortened with a series of wet, grinding sounds that made Nora look away. Ylva stood in the cold air, naked, steaming, her skin flushed.
Saijah silently offered her a cloak. Ylva took it and draped it over her shoulders for warmth. She did not bother to close the front or cover anything below the waist. Modesty had apparently not survived the transition to lycanthropy.
She wandered over to where Davinia was sitting and dropped down beside her, close enough that their shoulders touched. She didn't say anything about what had happened in the corridor. She didn't say anything about dying, or the beast inside her, or what it felt like to have your body rebuilt by a Daedric Prince without your consent.
She just sat there, warm and alive and unapologetically naked under a cloak she wasn't using correctly, and let Davinia decide whether to talk about it or not.
The Student
Nora found Alfonso after Ylva left him behind the pines. He was sitting against a tree, eyes closed, breathing the careful, measured breaths of someone managing pain on a moment-to-moment basis. One hit point. His body was a house of cards held together by will and two warring divine frequencies that had found a common note long enough to fire one impossible spell.
"What you did in the ruin," Nora said. She was standing at the edge of his space, hands clasped, the black soul gems catching the firelight. "The blast. That wasn't Focus. That wasn't Magicka. You used your life force."
Alfonso opened one eye.
"I want to learn how to do that," she said.
He looked at her for a long moment. The girl who was afraid of her own power asking the man who had almost killed himself with his to teach her how to burn.
"Sit down," he said.
She sat. And he taught her. Not Conjuration — she had that, she had always had that, and what she needed was not more power but more tools. He taught her the architecture of the spell he'd used. How to reach past Magicka into the well of vitality that every living thing carried. How to convert life into energy — not efficiently, not cleanly, but absolutely, the way a burning building converts wood into heat. It was a technique that cost health instead of Focus. It was a technique that could kill you.
Nora absorbed it the way she absorbed everything — with terrifying speed and the specific intensity of a mind that operated on a level most mages couldn't comprehend. By the time Alfonso's strength gave out and he had to stop talking, she understood the theory. The practice would come later. And it would cost her.
The Prayer
Saijah walked away from the fire and found a flat stone overlooking the foothills. The stars were bright — the first clear sky since Winterhold. She could see the northern lights dancing on the horizon, green and purple, the same colours that had lit the College's magical shields.
She knelt. Pressed her palms to the stone. Reached for Kynareth.
The goddess answered the way she always answered — not with words, not with visions, but with presence. The feeling of wind in a closed room. The scent of rain on dry earth. The specific, maternal warmth of being held by something vast and patient and infinitely sorrowful.
Saijah asked what she needed to do. Where to go. What came next. She asked about the roots — the dying network, the Dagon cult's corruption, the Eldergleam failing. She asked about Kyboh. She asked about Riften. She asked about Danica.
Kynareth gave her the same answer she always gave. Stop the corruption. Protect the roots. Heal what can be healed.
Nothing new. No new information. No new directives. The same instructions she'd been carrying since the day the migraine started, repeated without elaboration, as if the goddess either couldn't or wouldn't say more.
Saijah opened her eyes. The stars were unchanged. The migraine pulsed behind her left eye — stronger now, the pressure building as they moved south toward more compromised root network.
She was frustrated. She was tired. She had sacrificed her holy artifacts, lost a friend, fought through a ruin full of machines, and the goddess who had saved her life in the Midden couldn't be bothered to update her mission briefing.
She went back to the fire and slept.
The War-Hound
Davinia couldn't sleep. She sat by the dying fire while the others rested, flexing the Wizard Hand, watching the ice-crystal fingers catch the light. Ylva had finally passed out beside her, wrapped in the cloak, snoring softly.
Bjorn was still awake. He was sitting on the far side of the fire, smoking a cigar — not his usual pipe, something he'd been saving. The smoke rose straight in the still air.
Davinia moved to sit across from him. They were quiet for a while.
"You said something earlier," she said. "About Kyboh reminding you of yourself."
Bjorn drew on the cigar. The ember glowed orange in the dark.
"Aye."
"What does that mean?"
He was quiet for a long time. Long enough that she thought he wouldn't answer.
"A long time ago," he said, "they called me the War-Hound."
He said it like he was admitting to a crime. The name sat in the air between them, heavy with a weight she could feel but not measure.
"I was fast. Faster than anyone had a right to be. I could outrun cavalry. Cover ground that should have taken days in hours. The Legion used me for the jobs they didn't want on the official record. Impossible targets. Fortified positions. Things that needed to disappear."
He looked at the cigar in his hand.
"That was a lifetime ago. Several lifetimes. I buried the War-Hound in the Rift and spent forty years learning how to be a person instead of a weapon."
"What happened?"
"I made a promise to someone. Two someones. Young. Scared. I told them they'd be safe as long as I was breathing."
His voice was steady. Practiced. He had told himself this story enough times that the words came without the wound — or at least without the wound showing.
"They were taken. Right in front of me. And I was fast — faster than you'd believe looking at me now. And I wasn't fast enough."
He stopped. Drew on the cigar. Let the smoke out slowly.
"I found them. It was too late."
He didn't elaborate. The five words carried the weight of what he'd found, and Davinia — who could see auras, who could read intent in surfaces, who carried an ancient consciousness in her skull — didn't need him to say more. The shape of the trauma was visible in the way he held himself. In the way he'd never let Saijah call him father. In the way he'd watched Kyboh with the specific, helpless love of a man who recognised his younger self and knew exactly how the story ended.
"The kid was like me," Bjorn said quietly. "Fast. Strong. Stupid in all the right ways. Threw himself at things without thinking. Laughed when he should have been scared. Reminded me of someone I used to be before I learned that being fast doesn't mean being fast enough."
Davinia pulled the dragonbone shard from her pack. One of the four pieces of Kyboh's broken greatsword — a fragment of dragon bone, dense and warm, still carrying the faint tonal resonance of the enchantment that had lived in the blade.
"Kyboh would want you to have this," she said.
She held it out. Bjorn looked at the shard. Then at her. Then he took it.
The moment his fingers closed around the dragonbone, Davinia saw it.
Through the Wizard Sight — through Ismara's eyes — she watched Bjorn's soul react to the bone. The massive, blinding aura that surrounded him — already impossibly bright, already burning with a power she didn't understand — reached for the dragonbone the way a flame reaches for fuel. The tonal signature of the bone synchronized with something inside Bjorn's body. Not slowly. Not gradually. Instantly. The way Kyboh's bones had synchronized with the Anchor of Stasis before Hjolmar's forge.
The exact same harmonic lock. The exact same resonance pattern. Dragon bone meeting dragon soul.
Bjorn didn't notice. He turned the shard over in his hands, ran his thumb along the edge, and tucked it into his coat pocket.
"Thank you," he said. "I'm grateful."
Across the camp, Orion looked up from sharpening his blade. He glanced at Bjorn. At the shard. At the way the old man's hands were steady and strong in a way they hadn't been a week ago.
"Guys," he said to nobody in particular. "What if Bjorn is the Dragonborn?"
Nobody listened. Saijah was asleep. Alfonso was unconscious. Nora was reading. Davinia heard him, but she was staring at Bjorn's aura with Ismara's eyes and feeling the Crown's attention sharpen to a point — the ancient researcher suddenly very, very interested in what she'd just witnessed.
The Crown said nothing. But the silence was the loudest thing at the fire.
The Hunt
Orion went hunting. He needed blood. The fight and the escape and the lift had left him depleted in ways that rest alone couldn't fix. The Ring of the Pale Regent pulsed cold on his finger — Valerius always aware of the hunger, always watching.
Ylva chose to join him. She rose from the fire, dropped the cloak she'd barely been wearing, and transformed. The shift was smoother this time — faster, more controlled, as if her body was learning the new shape. Nine feet of werewolf stood in the firelight, amber eyes finding Orion's with an intelligence that was entirely Ylva.
They moved into the foothills together. The vampire and the werewolf, hunting side by side. It should have been absurd. It was, in a way that neither of them would have admitted.
They found a hunter — a lone Nord, making camp in a hollow between two boulders. Ylva, in a gesture of unexpected courtesy, held back. She let Orion approach first. The vampire's right. Feed first. She would take what was left.
But Orion wanted to feed live. The hunter felt him coming — the instinct that prey animals carry, the specific tightening of the spine that says something is wrong. The man fought back. Not well enough to win, but well enough to make the feeding messy and unsatisfying.
Orion made a decision. He froze the hunter solid — a blast of frost magic that turned the struggling man into a statue of ice, blood crystallising in his veins, his expression locked in mid-resistance.
Then he drank him like a slushy.
Ylva watched this happen. The werewolf's expression — insofar as a wolf face could express disappointment — conveyed a very specific kind of disgust. Not moral disgust. Practical disgust. She couldn't eat frozen meat. The hunt was ruined.
She turned and loped into the darkness, leaving Orion alone with his ice sculpture and the sound of vampire teeth on frozen blood. She would hunt on her own. She would find something warm.
Orion stood in the dark with frost on his lips and the ring burning cold on his finger and wondered, not for the first time, whether the creature he was becoming was worth the cost of the creatures around him.
The Dagger
Alfonso waited until the camp was quiet. Until Nora was asleep with her head on her pack and the black soul gems dim against her chest. Until Saijah's breathing had steadied into the rhythm of deep rest. Until Bjorn had finished his cigar and was dozing on the driver's bench.
He walked away from the fire. Not far. Just far enough that the light didn't reach him.
He knelt in the dark and reached for Namira.
The Daedric Prince of decay, of revulsion, of the ancient darkness that lives in the spaces between things. His patron. His crown-giver. The goddess who had taken his sensation of satedness and poured her essence into the dragon bone on his skull.
She answered. Not with words — Namira didn't use words the way mortals understood them. She answered with hunger. A vast, hollow, infinite hunger that filled Alfonso's chest and pressed outward against his ribs like something trying to be born.
You are my hunger incarnate. Together, we will devour the world.
Alfonso looked at the iron dagger in his hand. His family's dagger. The blade he'd carried since before the College, before the plague, before any of it. Simple iron. Unenchanted. The most unremarkable weapon in his inventory.
He had watched Hjolmar enchant with tonal architecture. He had watched Sergius enchant with soul gems. He had enchanted the Jagged Crown himself, trading his satedness for Namira's mark.
He didn't have a soul gem. He didn't have tonal architecture. He had something else.
He pressed the blade against his chest and reached into himself — past the plague, past the hunger, past the two songs fighting in his chest — and found the thing that lived at the centre of all of it. His soul. The unique, undefined, impossible soul of a man who was no longer a vampire and not yet anything else, carrying two divine frequencies in a mortal body that was tearing itself apart.
He used it.
The enchantment was not a spell. It was a transaction. Alfonso poured his soul into the iron dagger the way water pours into a vessel, and the dagger drank. The iron darkened. The blade lengthened, thinned, curved slightly — reshaping itself into a rapier as the enchantment remade the weapon in the image of what it was becoming. The simple iron became something corroded and ancient-looking, pitted with dark spots that might have been rust or might have been something alive.
His phylactery. The word came to him with a certainty that had nothing to do with knowledge and everything to do with the two divine frequencies that had just found their vessel. His soul was in the blade. His body was — empty wasn't the right word. His body was freed. No health to lose. No wounds to suffer. No physical damage that could reach the thing that mattered, because the thing that mattered was in the dagger now.
He was a lich. A lich of Peryite — an oxymoron, a paradox, a thing that shouldn't exist. The weakest possible lich. Not immortal. Undying. His body couldn't be hurt, but his iron rapier could be damaged, could rust, could corrode over time. He had made himself very short-lived but had given himself the ability to ignore physical destruction entirely.
The implications were staggering. And the cost was immediate — his connection to Namira weakened. He felt the Daedric Prince recoil as Peryite's order imposed structure on the chaos she craved. If it weren't for the Jagged Crown — the artifact he'd enchanted at Hjolmar's forge, the bridge between his two patrons — the competing divine frequencies would have torn him in half.
The Crown held. Barely. Two gods arguing over a dead man's soul through a crown made of dragon bone and a rapier made of iron and sacrifice.
Across the camp, Saijah's eyes snapped open. Something had changed in the world — a shift in the texture of the air, the way a lake's surface changes when a stone hits the bottom. She couldn't name what she'd felt. But it was wrong. New. Close.
Davinia, still awake, saw it through the Wizard Sight. Alfonso's aura — already a war zone of competing frequencies — had fundamentally restructured. The soul that had been burning inside his body was gone. Not destroyed. Relocated. She could see it in the blade he held — a rapier that blazed with the energy his body used to contain.
His body was dark. No aura. No life force. No soul.
Walking. Breathing. Dark.
She didn't say anything. Some observations are too large for a campfire in the foothills, and the man who'd just turned himself into something impossible probably didn't want to discuss it.
The Handler
Varon found Orion on his way back from the hunt. The Shadowscale materialised from the dark the way he always did — one moment the path was empty, the next he was there.
"Timeline?"
The word landed the way it always landed. A stone in still water.
Orion looked at him. Frost on his lips. Blood on his chin. The ring burning cold. Three masters pulling in three directions and none of them getting closer to resolution.
Varon's jaw was tight. The controlled frustration that had been building since the Winter Road was closer to the surface now — visible in the set of his modified features, in the tension of his hands.
"I want to go home, Orion. I am not adapted to the cold world of Skyrim and I am here until you finish your contract."
Orion gave him nothing. Vague words. Empty promises. The same deflection he always gave, because the truth — that he had no plan, no timeline, and no intention of killing Hroki — was something he couldn't say out loud without consequences.
Varon stared at him for a long moment. Then he turned and walked back toward camp.
He found Saijah awake, sitting at the edge of the fire's light, rubbing her eyes. He sat beside her.
"Vena."
She looked at him. He tried to flirt. Badly. The Shadowscale's social skills — perfectly adequate for manipulation, seduction, and the calculated deployment of charm — failed him when the charm was genuine. The words came out wrong. The smile was off-centre. The timing was terrible.
Saijah didn't laugh at him. She was too tired and too sad for cruelty. She just looked at him with the specific exhaustion of a woman who had sacrificed her holy artifacts and lost a friend and fought through eleven thousand spiders and was being courted by an assassin who couldn't figure out how to be a person instead of a weapon.
"I want to go to the Eldergleam," she said. "The roots are dying. Kynareth won't tell me anything new. I need to see the tree for myself."
Orion, passing on his way back to his bedroll, heard her. "That's... not where we're heading. I have a contract —"
Varon turned to him with a speed that made the sentence die.
"If Saijah wants to go somewhere," Varon said, his voice carrying the specific, quiet authority of a man who had just decided that his associate's priorities were no longer the primary concern, "we can go. No problem."
Orion opened his mouth. Closed it. The calculus of three masters had just shifted — Varon, who answered to the Brotherhood, was overriding the Brotherhood's timeline for Saijah.
The implications of that sat in the air between the three of them like a held breath.
Then a courier came up the road.
He was young, breathless, wearing the generic livery of the Skyrim courier service. He spotted Orion, pulled a sealed letter from his satchel, and held it out.
"Letter for you. From your employer."
Orion took it. Broke the seal. Read.
The contract for Grelod the Kind. The headmistress of Honorhall Orphanage in Riften. The woman the Dark Brotherhood wanted dead.
Another leash. Another obligation. Another reason to keep walking toward a city that didn't need saving, carrying a contract he didn't want to fulfill, wearing a ring that reported every heartbeat to a vampire lord who was always, always watching.
Orion tucked the letter into his coat and said nothing.
The Promise
Dawn was close. The fire was embers. Davinia was sitting with Bjorn on the driver's bench, watching the eastern horizon lighten from black to grey.
"I miss her," Davinia said.
She didn't say who. She didn't need to.
Bjorn was quiet for a moment. Then he said: "Danica is a good woman. Strong. The kind of strong that doesn't break — it bends, and then it straightens, and it's stronger than before."
He looked at his hands. Flexed them. The stiffness that had been there for years was gone. His fingers moved with a fluidity that belonged to a younger man.
"She'll come to her senses," he said. "I promise you that. Whatever happened between you — whatever you said or didn't say — it's not bigger than what she is. She's out there doing what she does. Healing. Protecting. Following the work wherever it takes her."
He put his hand on Davinia's shoulder. Warm. Steady. The grip of a man who had carried things heavier than comfort.
"You'll see her again, lass. And when you do, don't waste it on apologies. Just be there."
Davinia leaned into the warmth of his hand and felt, for one moment, the specific ache of a woman who had traded her mother's memory and her right hand and her human eyes for power, and would have traded all of it back for five minutes with a priestess she'd pushed away.
The Morning
They packed up. Bjorn finished his cigar. The camp was struck with the efficient, wordless cooperation of people who had done this dozens of times. GEAR narrated the process.
"The biological transport unit appears to have driven the conveyance autonomously during the nocturnal rest period. Is this standard operational behaviour?"
"Mable practically drives the cart herself," Bjorn said, climbing onto the bench. "I honestly sleep at the reins more often than not. Usually drinking too."
He grinned. It was the first time he'd smiled since they'd come out of the ruin.
They were off. The road entered the foothills — the transition zone between the Pale and the Rift, where frozen tundra gave way to the first hints of autumn colour. The air warmed by degrees. The sky was clear. Birds sang in the scrub pines.
Then the birds stopped.
Bjorn jerked upright on the bench. His hand went to his chest. His eyes went wide — not looking at the sky, not looking at the road, looking at nothing. Like a man who had just felt his heart skip.
"Something's —"
He didn't finish the sentence.
The shadow fell.
It passed over the cart like a stormcloud, blotting the pale morning light. Something enormous crossed the gap between the cliff walls of the narrowing pass — fast, deliberate, wingtips scraping stone with a shriek of scale on rock. Sparks showered down from both walls.
It dropped below the ridgeline. They saw it.
Scales the dark red-brown of dried blood, jagged and scarred from centuries of territorial combat. A wingspan that filled the pass wall to wall. Eyes — amber, burning, ancient — locked onto the cart. Onto them.
The jaws opened. The air between them darkened — something thick and reddish-black churning in the throat, not clean fire, something organic, crackling with a heat that smelled like hot iron and bile.
"ZU'U KROSULHAH. HI LOS NAHKIP WO KRII ZEYMAHI. TODAY HI DIR."
I am Krosulhah. You are the prey who killed my brother. Today you die.
He wasn't circling. He was diving.

— End of The Long Road Home —


